But I despise mob mentality and behaviors more than just about anything short of physical pain. Mobs not only hide truth but they bury it in blood. 

Fighting narratives with narratives isn't the answer.

The only path to truth - and, by extension, understanding and forgiveness - is through serious, intellectually honest dialogue.

Ask the guy the who, what, how and WHY.

I'm just a nobody writing Kings and NHL tweets. People with big platforms (ie hockey media) should do it.

Is he just a stupid human? Maybe just a stupid moment?

Is he just a bitter prejudiced person? Temporary or permanent?

Is he someone more sinister? Bigotry? Ignorance? Other?

All three are different. How can anyone even draw any conclusions without even knowing which is which?

Don't just report or tweet what others are claiming or saying. 

Do what a real journalist would do - do the hard work and report the actual story. The Truth. 

Otherwise, you're no better than him or anyone else on the wrong end of a delirious mob attack. You're a whore.

I'm aware that I'll get criticized for this view. I'll be called a clown. I've been called anything and everything nasty before. That's how people are online. 

That's fine. If we don't speak up, truth has no chance. You can wind up siding with a mob of assholes against one jerk.

This doesn't hold up as a legal argument, I'll explain below. Not even close. The "foes" claims about environmental impacts should be dismissed summarily, and I'm not sure it looks good for a news outlet to take them at face value except for gossipy nonsense. üßµ https://t.co/twitter_link

See, the real and immediate answer to this is to just cap hourly trips along the highways for vehicles with carbon emissions, and force overflow vehicles to power down in a waiting area. People would HATE that but that's the actual legal remedy to "too much car pollution"

You could not practically uphold the "right to clean air" in all places in the state, and we certainly don't have that now. And a constitution that implies that the rights of some are in direct competition with the rights of others has some very very bad architecture

But let's move past the amendment being faulty, because it was ratified and the courts must respect it. I'd prefer that they did. So... who is the respondent in a claim about dirty air along highways? The MTA... or the drivers?

NYS Constitution Article 1 ¬ß19 "Environmental rights. Each person shall have a right to clean air and water, and a healthful environment." I argued to vote against this constitutional amendment when it came out precisely because this is childish logic that obstructs governance.
You can also do it by narrowing the expressways, but that will just shift pollution to entrance ramp queues if the claimants are to be believed.

But... should we believe them?

Congestion pricing is absolutely meant to reduce trips regionally, not just send everyone a bill for them. 

The MTA is not predicting broad increases in traffic & their findings are that the range of outcomes lies mostly in "less trips everywhere"

So, the estimate is that there will be no significant negative impacts in pollution anywhere. 

The Feds signed a memo concurring with these findings. After 4.5 years of review.

But then there is so much more that happens in day-to-day administration, infrastructure and human activity that would run afoul of this test... e.g. never any more parades, no bike lanes, no bridge repairs, no funerals, etc.

The claimants are counting on a judge to look past all of these facts and established legal theories just to say, "a toll adjustment cannot have an effect of shifting traffic within its realm of possibilities or else it is unconstitutional"

üö® üßµ Kings vs Oilers: The Hardcore Preview

I don't like how Edmonton is looking. Skinner is off his usual form. The recent line mixing has them discombobulated. 

We are catching them at the right time. Let's look at why the Kings have been on a tear lately.

It's not about the 1-3-1 but rather it's the other number ... the 11-7.

The 11-7 has kept our blueliners fresh. That's what the extra Dman does. It's the 11-7 added on top of the 1-3-1 that has stifled teams.

All of the attention has gone to Arvidsson and rightly so.

But, Mikey's return has been huge. He adds an edge to our squad and his stick work and board work has been nothing short of impeccable. He's an agitator. Gavrikov also finally looks healthy.

It'll be difficult to score 5v5 against this back end.

Now, the forward lines. We finally have three solid lines to roll out. Arvidsson's return has settled in all three lines.

Each line has a playmaker, two way center, and a scorer. Yes, Dubois is unburdened with scoring so he's playmaking the way he knows how.

I'd still like to see him stop roaming up high and support down low but we'll take whatever we can get for now.

The firmness of the 3 lines has given Hiller the flexibility he needs to deploy Lizotte and Lewis in key spots. Namely, he can use them after lines get shuffled ...

due to PP and PKs. The immediate shifts after penalty time used to disrupt our lines but that's no longer the case. Another reason why 11-7 has allowed for stability, continuity, and fresh shifts. 

I'm also seeing better shift management in terms of zone starts.

While the media and opposing fans have been newly obsessed with the 1-3-1 the fact is the Kings aren't in that zone trap set for more than 15-18 minutes per game. It's a red herring.

We are mostly in a 3-2 if you watch closely. That's why the dump ins are ineffective.
When you find out someone else you know is a $DJT shareholder https://t.co/twitter_link

We're anticipating the dump ins and that's been helping our breakouts. In a 1-3-1 dispossession in the neutral zone for a quick counterattack is the main objective.

With 3-2 hybrid defense, we're sitting back even more (ie, no man forechecking in their zone) and getting ...

takeaways and making passes to a breaking forward near the blue line. This is how our chances are being created.

In summary, I'm liking everything the Kings are doing.

The effort level is high. The stick work is terrific. Stick checks, stick lifts, stick pokes.

By physicality, I don't mean hitting. The Kings are still awful at letting opposing players just cruise in front of the net and park there. That cannot happen. We need to either get to that real estate and box out or use body weight leverage and constantly keep them imbalanced.

We're being smart with shots and not turning over the puck with dumb shots that turn into rush chances the other way.

The two things we're still doing poorly is (a) physicality and (b) making quicker decisions.

Our passing has improved dramatically.

Byfield-Kopitar-Kempe line will continue to dominate both ways.

I believe that line will see the RNH-McDavid-Hyman line much of the game. 

Kings 2 vs Oilers 3
Kings 1 vs Oilers 1
Kings 3 vs Oilers 2
Kings 4 vs Oilers 4.

Only the Draisaitl line (line 2) has a significant edge.

I see the Kings absolutely crushing Edmonton tonight.

I know that's a controversial opinion that can make this thread age like vinegar wine.

But, having gone through my process, all signs point to a Kings game.

Prediction?

Kings 5, Oilers 2.

If the Kings find a way to lose, it'll be due to Enrique-Draisaitl-Foegele. That's a very physical line without speed.

If Dubois line decides not to defend up tight, we'll be destroyed and be forced to chase the game for two periods.

So, yes, I can see us also losing 2-5.

It's too hard to overlook the fact that Kings form is A+ and Oilers form is B-.

Skinner looks shaky as hell. Talbot looks like a titanium.

Kings will win this game.

Btw - WTF are the Angels doing leading off with Rendon and sitting Rengifo? Incredibly stupid.

The dump in is the LAST option for teams that cannot do the first two. https://t.co/twitter_link

1. Skate through the zone defense through the CENTER of the ice for entry. (ie, it can't be along the boards). Elite puck handlers with exceptional skating abilities (eg, McDavid).

2. Use speed to get through the double coverage by passing to self along the boards.

3. When those two things keep failing, you dump and chase the puck. Usually there's a last man back you have to win the puck from. 

Edmonton has a line that can bust the 1-3-1 down the middle (McDavid) and big wingers with speed who can bust through along the boards.

Kane and even Draisaitl will do this repeatedly.

All kids are taught defense in every sport because most are too young to be great offensively. This is self fulfilling. It makes offense tougher since the defense is relatively strong. Go watch any pee wee or JV game. It's a comedy of errors.

As the kids get older ...

a few kids get offensively dominant. Coaches work on these strengths to elevate them above the rest. This is also self fulfilling. 

The focus on playing to their strengths makes them even more offensively strong.

Players must stand out this way to get a chance to break through.

This is no different than any other career.

We rise to the level of our incompetence then need to remake ourselves. 

Those who stubbornly resist change get left behind. 

Career arcs are really a series of cycles.

Once the offensive players reach the top leagues it reverts back to the beginning.

Surrounded by other apex predators they have to go back to working on their weaknesses.

Most athletes can't or won't do it. 

Athletic careers have to be closely managed.
